segments.text: And she said that she did see me.
She watched that match.
And that match was a five-set match.
Three out of five.
And she said she did see me.
But I didn't see her.
I was probably busy.
But I remember looking around for her.
Because I wanted to impress her with my tennis.
And she said she didn't see me.
And we did get called up on our date.
I went to the wrong place, or she went to the wrong place.
So we had a date.
I was there.
Where were you?
You know, that kind of thing.
I have to step aside from coming back to my father.
Not coming to the tennis courts, particularly.
Due to lack of time, they'd be tired.
So maybe they're on to my town.
But I spent a great deal of time on those courts.
Hanging around, even on a rainy day, waiting for them to dry.
which bunk was she in the same bunk were you sitting standing lying uh oh we may have been
lying side by side looking to keep warm it was an affectionate thing yeah it was you know obviously she must have had some

like towards me to ask me for protection but and she was an attractive girl and like I said she was I think she had either a doctorate or some degree of psychology so she was a career woman I remember she had wore even one of those wool dresses so
were popular in those days, a knobby kind of thing, textured school dress, expensive magnet type thing, nice clothes.
Even in that little resort that was just trying to make it, I was trying to latch onto it and get my own school going.
The other question would have to do with your early teaching skin in this country.
You said you were teaching people who were with the Sierra Club and wanted to know how to get back to their cabins.
Were these people who you taught one-on-one, or did you have masking classes of people?
What was that like?
A variety.
Anything from one-on-one that's private lessons to 30, like every Easter, the board of directors would come up with their children.
tiny tots up and bring their children over the Easter weekend and just dump them on me so that they could go skiing somewhere else.
And I had these thirty kids for four or five years, probably.
And I became, they were so thrilled with their progress.
And I had a little race at the end of the week, of the Easter week, which we were putting the poles in a triangle and they had to go under it because that's what we were doing as kids.
and see all the things that we were doing when I was teaching.
And they loved it.
And that's where this gal, Shafi, was in that class and later became an Olympic skier.
Several of those kids made it to Dartmouth and to, yeah, onto the Olympic team because I met the lady of the president of the Sierra Club, lived in Berkeley, and I visited her.
In fact, I was invited to her daughter's wedding, and I just feel terrible because I never gave her a present.
I didn't have any money.
I was invited to her daughter's present.
She was also in that class.
Yes, I think Dorothy Leonard.
Jean, Dorothy, something like that.
Leonard.
Dick Leonard is the president of this year of this chapter, or maybe the national, I don't know.
But he was an attorney.

and lived in the Berkeley Hills, in a lovely home overlooking the bay, and they would gather up and they thought, the world of me, how marvelous, and the kids all love me, you know, and they became champions in their own right after that, giving him a good foundation, fun,
Control, coordination, the fundamentals.
What was your teaching style?
Did you stick with the techniques a lot, or did you stop and tell jokes and stories in between?
The whole thing.
I believe in the whole thing.
Maintain, get their attention and hold it, and you can only hold it by a variety of things instead of harping on one thing.
You wanted to mention the same kind of relationship activities with Junior Davis.
I did the same thing in APTIS.
I had Junior Davis come volunteer.
Volunteer.
Volunteer to, came, a question came through from the, from the main,
tennis association from San Francisco if I would start a Junior Davis Cup team in my area there, and I accepted the assignment.
Mark was there, and I hired several, two or three local guys, Mark, to help me, and we had, oh God, how many, 40, 50 kids, boys and girls.
And you took a program to, a similar program to Watsonville?
Yes, I had a similar program, because a lady, the principal of a school from Watsonville, turned out to be a former national champion.
Barbara Hedlund, a ranked player.
And she found out about this club that we started.
This was kind of a community that was not really into sports very much until Gina and I got in there.
They had a little, but we really got it going.
And Barbara Hedlund, they came kind of out of the woodwork, all these people that had been semi-retired.
It was a retirement community, actually.
She and I played doubles together, and we beat everybody.
I mean, we could have gone on and gotten our own national ranking, but she had personal problems with her husband.
And she and I would just scream at her.
But that would have put you in a bad position because you would have gotten too much visibility.
It would have been national publicity again.
It was probably a good thing that whatever problems she had kept you from doing it.
She was in national women's levels.
Yeah, she was national.
Yeah, she was already ranked.
But her school, she asked if I would run a tennis program in Watsonville for her school after ours, which I did.
You were single all that time.
How did you spend your time when you weren't?
No, no.
Oh, okay.
Before that then, backing up to the point that you were still single with the skiing and all, how did you spend your time when you weren't teaching?
Well, usually looking for girls and food, good restaurants to eat because I didn't know how to cook.
read, and usually girl watching, and maybe going to a dance here and there.
So you go to public places a lot.
Public places, and then would get involved with my own projects.
I'd make up projects and involve myself unknowingly, like making movies, getting an 8mm camera and
I discovered a flaw in my backhand in those days and straightened that out.
I got myself a new backhand by taking movies, taking movies of all the top players.
I have movies of guys that are now on television.
Tony Trabert, his partner Talbert who runs the
who was the tournament director for the U.S. Open in New York City.
All these guys, they have movies.
I studied all their technique.
So I got in these, and I made ski movies.
I found a girl that she always kids me about because she looks older than she is.
She kept showing up in these movies, good-looking, and she was a little Jewish girl about...
no more than 15 years old,
very good-looking and radiant.
Can I tell a quick anecdote about that movie and that girl?
As I indicated, he had never told me very much of anything, and would shy a hedge on any questions about relationships.

So right after we got the job as the pro at Beaver's Racquet, the first pro tennis pro job in Santa Cruz County, and we started generating some social activities around this little membership project.
One of the things we did would be to have a mixed doubles night and then everybody would bring a jug of wine and we'd have some food and sit around and socialize.
And he decided he wanted to show some of these little skate movies, which I had not seen.
So I'm helping him.
We're getting the projector out and all of a sudden up here on the screen, it's repeating this picture of him
with this girl somewhere in the group or together with her and the whole crowd and I really crack up because I said, who is that woman?
And I've introduced other females.
You see, I broke the rule.
You see?
And it can only cause trouble.
It never turns out right.
And her name was Wolf.
I can't think of her name, but her name was Wolf, spelled W-O-L-F-F.
Very young girl who
full of enthusiasm for my project.
She was actually volunteered to be an assistant.
What are we going to do today, Dennis, type of thing.
Show up at your door.
What are we going to shoot today?
What story?
So she was a perfect foil partner for me to get involved in other projects and have a marvelous time making movies, which I showed on Saturday nights to hundreds of people.
instructional movies, cartoons.
They would come up, okay, let's make a cartoon.
She'd make a clown costume for me so that I could play the clown.
I would make skis out of barrel pieces, staves, nail old shoes to it so I could ski backwards and things like that and fall down and all the audience would just roar, you know?
And I had bought a recorder, and I remember the songs I recorded as background music to the ski movies.
Pergin Suite makes a marvelous downhill race.
I filmed the Silver Belt, famous race of Trigger Boat, every year with some of the top racers in it.
Did you watch a lot of movies, Lee Camp?
Yeah, as many as we got, these Hollywood movies.
Marvelous, free movies.
Can't beat that.
Did any of them stick with you?
I can't think of one offhand, but you've got to know the movie stars that kept coming back, the faces, and the Hollywood productions were great.
We didn't see any other, not one camp incident that you read about.
They showed us the horror movies that I know of of these concentration camps.
We never saw one of those.
So we were nothing but good front movies playing there.
We veered away from Ms. Wolf successfully.
Is there anything about, you can say, look, I don't know anything about Wolf.
Nothing whatsoever.
I considered her much too young.
Just because she looked mature and acted mature, she wasn't.
She did take me to meet their parents in San Francisco.
and they turned out to, they were engaged in some kind of political thing, I could tell.
There was something going on, and I didn't really want to get involved.
He was a professor of some sort at the time.
It was during the era that all of the... What, McCarthyism?
Might have been, might have been.
I just, and that's only just guesswork.
They were involved in some books and paper and all this intellectual stuff, and laying around, and here's this young,
girl, you know, introducing me, and I believe we had dinner, and she must have told him that she had a lot of fun up at the Sierra Club with this guy, you know, making movies.
I would assume that's the way to open it up.
But I'm sure...
If you had joined a political party, what party would you have joined?
None.
Do you feel yourself, if someone says...
Yeah, the Republicans are doing this and that.
Do you feel more akin?
Yeah, I have.
Someone says the Democrats are doing this and that.
You say, gee, I would support that.
Yeah, I do.
I do feel about issues.
something that was unknown, this terminology.
In fact, I had a conversation with my niece as I was reading these, since I started reading some German newspaper that says, they still don't know how to write published newspapers.
All they can talk about is, first of all, their words are too long.
Nobody can understand them.
And she agreed, yeah, that their sight is a,
a terrible newspaper.
No, it doesn't have to go on.
No, okay.
Because the words are too long.
And they never have any issues.
Where is the issue?
They're looking for issues.
And then get the different sides to the issue.
What they have is a Gesprch, which is an interview.
That is a one side.
Well, where in the hell is the other side?
Or what other?
You know, where is the... A Gesprch is a pretty...
Well, it's not a good tool to enlighten people.
It's okay.
I may be interested in what a certain person has to say, but where's the issue?
It's the newspaper's job to dig out the issues.
Yes.
Which party would you find yourself with if you were involved in American politics?
I guess I'm not going to do that.
No, I don't.
You're asking me a straight question.
Just where do you...
the cross-section, the ethnic thing.
Very much, Gene and I, just without knowing, ever discussing politics prior to our marriage, we just think alike.
One more lucky thing that happened.
Let me ask you, during the times that you were a ski instructor, when
Would the apprehension start about what you're going to do during the summer?
About January, February, March?
Are you starting to get worried about March?
March, yeah.
You're saying, I'm getting concerned.
First of May is the last.
I see.
So first of May is the end of the season.
Yeah.
So you have to start concerning yourself with what you're going to do this summer.
My God, how am I going to stay alive?
Well, and usually I had no prospects.
So I tried to save as much money, which wasn't very much because these jobs are low-level kind of jobs as far as money is concerned.
Right.
How would you go about preparing yourself for May 1st?
I was saving as much as I could.
And then this goes usually straight for Stockton, which is in the middle of the San Joaquin Valley and the agricultural community.

So if worse came to worse, if I didn't plan to come up with anything, then I'd just jump on the truck at 5 o'clock in the morning and go out to wherever we were, find a supply truck, work, pay home, leave.
Was it a scary prospect to leave the security of skiing traumatic?
Was there a one time in particular that you remember that
boy, I'm not looking forward to this summer at all.
I just don't feel good, I don't have enough money, or I'm leaving this girl, or I'm... Yeah, you have to leave your friendship with these beautiful girls.
There was one season, you know, the one that I met this gal from Sacramento, and... Who was that?
Pardon?
Who was that?
The girl from Sacramento?
The girl from Sacramento where Bill Klein told me not to get involved.
Oh, yes, right.
Any rich girls.
Psychologist.
Psychologist.
No, that was in Pendley Hill.
The psychology was in Pendley Hill.
She was the one that was the advertising manager for the Thailand Country Shopping Center in Sacramento, a brand new shopping center.
And she wrote a column.
the shopping center column about people, that they still use today, that technique, which, of course, was totally new to me.
This merchandising technique was my first introduction to business advertising, an American way of doing business.
I found it fascinating.
And she was crazy about this guy.
She thought he was a genius.
to do all these things.
And of course, I'm sure he had two or three Cadillacs and was a big businessman in Sacramento.
So that was a tough time.
That was a tough season for him.
You have to give up this entree by being able to get into this kind of business world that was so fascinating and rewarding, obviously, because they were all
driving around in fancy cars, and I probably didn't even have a car.
And you were dating already with her?
Yeah, yeah, a few dates.
But it's very hard to take them out when you don't have any money.
There's certain things to be expected, dinner, movies.
So you were pretty close, and you knew that when summer came, when May 1st came, you'd have to leave.
and you would not see her again, unless she showed up for the next season.
Yeah, pretty much so.
And so it was pretty hard to, I mean, one assumed that once May 1st rolled around and you started your summer work, that she wouldn't wait around.
Chances are you wouldn't see her again the next season.
Which was correct, because she didn't get married to some wealthy guy from Milwaukee, dear family.
How did you find that out?
I did meet her.
Either I called her or she called me, and...
when I was on the peninsula.
That surprised me.
After she'd gotten married, she wanted to see me, wanted to know what I was doing.
How long after that?
Five years?
That was amazing that she was interested enough to...
I'm trying to think, honey.
I remember we had lunch.
We met for lunch up at...
fish market up at North Shore, the beach in San Francisco, North Beach.
I remember being late for lunch and I had to apologize.
We had French bread and the famous lunch.
You were married by that time or not?
No.
That must have been a scary thing to have someone call you out of the past because you have to stop and think, what did I tell her the first time?
What have I done since then?
Well, it was getting better.
I was accumulating a better...
I mean, I had more to tell now.
I had a life that I could talk about.
I had a job.
I was doing interesting things myself.
So it was actually, you know, every year it was getting better.
It seemed like it wasn't, but it was.
What were you doing at that time on the peninsula?

I was estimating, so it had to be after Herb died, and I'd already moved to, because Herb was in East Bay, Oakland, and then I got a job with AMCO, which had a place in Oakland, but they also had a place on the peninsula, and they transferred me to the peninsula across the bay, and I moved into San Mateo, and...
I left them for Clark Door, which was a cabinet and pre-hung door shop, similar to what Earl had, only more cabinets and things.
And so I worked for these Clark boys.
They had hired me away from somebody
I had been a competitor of theirs and what I would do is I would go to my competitors and surprisingly they would offer me jobs because I was hurting them.
Sure.
So they would say, okay, why don't you bring over your clients to mine?
We need the business.
We'll give you $15 more.
What are you making?
And they would up my salary a little bit, and I would bring as many clients as I could over to the next guy.
So when somebody was hassling me or they wanted to put the screws to me, then I would look for a competitor and take my clients with me.
Is it hard for you to leave people?
My friends, yes, but when they put the screws to me, no.
And can you usually find a reason why they're putting the screws to you?
What I'm curious about is, does the decision to leave come first, and then looking for a good reason, they're hassling me?
Remember that time they said this and this and this, and then you create, you engineer a reason to leave you.
Does the leaving come first, or does the hassling come first?
The hassling comes first.
Oh, okay.
So you begin to feel that they really are down on you for some reason?
You know how management is.
You're talking about people that know very little more than you do, are in charge of you.
Right.
So I don't, you know, and I'm also in many...
cases, as Gene finally pointed out to me, is that I'm usually a threat to them.
I usually threaten my own managers.
So in those days I was very outspoken, and I still am, which is not very smart.
I'm not skilled in the corporate
gameplay.
I read books.
I try to learn like Peter's Principle and things like that.
I try to get away from my bluntness and use more diplomacy.
And Jean helps me with that a lot.
But it's hard for you to leave people, or it's not?
It just depends on how they...
I want to add a little something here.
To...
to me, he has very often said or expressed his attitude that if somebody does something like that to him, they don't exist anymore.
And I've seen him do this.
They simply do not exist.
I have the same opinion.
Yeah, I could, you know, they just died.
Yeah.
And so there have been a lot of times when maybe that influenced me, too.
I didn't really think that that would happen to us, but that if I did hassle them too much, I would not exist.
Right.

and i thought then when finally we got down to that point where i was ready that was included what was going to happen i would walk out the door and i would no longer exist well that wouldn't exactly have happened but the impression is this all with everybody or is that just the selected no this is selected to get out of the situation uh you can't you can't go on disliking somebody and

worrying about it and you've got to get on and change get out of the situation and the best way is to just to leave to leave and but you never had the feeling that gee i wish i'd left a note or gee i wish i had sent a postcard yeah with a lot of those like i said just in a very
with the people that are especially very, very kind to me, super sweet people, talk to a bunch of people that I feel bad about.
But even the ones I had hassles with, I didn't really want to hassle.
I didn't realize I was threatening anybody for their jobs.
Maybe I was.
I wanted to get a better job, true.
But I didn't realize that they thought I was getting after their job.
I just wanted a better job.
But they feel always threatened.
So that was news to me.
Once I learned that, that helped me a lot.
Not much.
Let me ask you a question about the time you spent in Berkeley.
It sounds like a very important period.
Yes.
It sounds as though you were coming out.
Yes.
I'm going to go downstairs.
Yeah.
That was a marvelous experience.
About when was that?
I was working for her at the time.
Because my first decent job, steady job, steady paycheck, none of us worrying about the summer and winter.
So I had to be 53, 54 at the time slot.
And so Herb played tennis, not as much as I did, because he worried about his business on Saturday.
He'd go in and work a few hours.
And I would go in once in a while, but not all the time.
And on these courts, I met all these foreign students or ex-students that stayed over.
Lowell Welsh.
these guys that hang around the tennis courts.
Right.
Put me in that place.
You are living in Berkeley, or are you living around Berkeley?
Could I just go for the thing?
Oh, sure, sure.
Now it's on.
Okay.
Let me ask you about Berkeley.
That sounds like an important period.
Very.
First of all, it had all the ingredients of...
early Greek and its freedom of expression, symposiums.
I had some, you know, I could talk about

those things a little bit, because I had known about, I had heard about Greeks, I had the history, and I knew what symposium meant, and I knew what freedom of expression meant, and standing up, and having, voicing your opinion.
How did you find yourself in Berkeley?
I had tried San Francisco, and
Of course, I checked out, I'm constantly checking out, looking for places.
And I had liked Berkeley.
As soon as I drove into town, or rather the bus came into town, Lake Merritt is right in the middle, lovely place.
And the people, it's more residential, less business oriented, the downtown area.
And I had a good feeling about the town.
And, of course, I think it must have been with Herb, because Herb was in East Oakland on 33rd Street.
That was my first job on that side of the bay.
And I had been there, through there, because Berkeley is on that side.
And these people lived there, the director of the Sierra Club.
Oh, someone's coming.
How much time do we have here?
So you're in Berkeley.
You came in by bus.
Herb said, I got a car, company kind of car I could use to go make calls with.
And like I say, the first two weeks I had this accident with it, practically demolished the whole front end of it.
Well, that was the old Plymouth.
Yeah, the old Plymouth.
Yeah.
And...

So I had the whole territory, the whole Bay Area, which is five million people, that I, he says, I don't, after the first week of looking around in the shop for how we manufacture this product, he says, you can get out and find some work.
I need the work.
Right.
I got all these doors here.
We got to sell them.
Right.
didn't really give me a few hints as to where to go, who to see, you know, and the rest of it is up to you.
I just started to prowl the area for jobs, and I developed an eye for any kind of raw lumber within my vision.
When I see a two by four, I know there has to be some construction going on.
And I enjoyed that very much.
Just this independence, this freedom.
Nobody hassling you while you're out looking.
And the searching was part of my
The prowling around for something was part of my makeup anyway.
So it fell right into my moving, not standing still and waiting to be discovered.
Yes.
The flight almost like a salesman is a hunter itself.
Yes, I see that too.
To find jobs.
Yeah, to find jobs.
So that fell right into it.
So I was successful from the beginning.
He was always amazed at the new jobs that I would find.
How did you run into Turk and these people?

So then, on weekends, I lived in the middle of town, which is between, the job was in East Oakland, I lived in Lake Merritt in a boarding house, and always looking, finding things, where's tennis courts, checked out Davies Stadium, the one that's in Merritt, Lake Merritt, it's a city-run place, and I was very cliquish, I could not get in,
very well.
They played with each other, and the tennis players were very cliquish.
I got to play a little bit, but not enough, so I was looking for other courts.
Found some in Alameda, friendly people, the Irish people.
He became national
ranked, was on the Davis Cup team.
He'd just been returned from the, he was junior champion, and I met his mother and father, they were running his courts.
They took me in, played some tennis in Alameda, which is a peninsula there.
But I remember distinctly in those days,

that cars were driving all around these courts, that I had difficulty serving, because when you served, I had to take my eyes off the traffic, if you can imagine watching the traffic while playing tennis.
And it always has bothered me to take my eye... Off the ball.
Off the traffic, off my surroundings.
Because at that time, I felt very...
and I have difficulty.
I wanted to be able, I wanted to play and see is there a car parked over there, is there somebody watching me, that kind of thing.
When did you live at Black Mirror?
What year was that?
In the early part.
What year?
Did I ever tell you that in 1959 I lived on Bandana Boulevard about four or five blocks from where we're driving?
It never stops, does it?
So a lot of it is just moving around.
One man down in Boulevard, Mr. Bob Lake Merritt, and he's talking about a groovy house that was right in that...
Manzanito.
Manzanita?
Manzanita.
What's that?
Tree or?
Manzanita.
Manzanita.
And I lived on Man Man.
Yeah, had to be very close.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
So you got in with a bunch of Berkeley students?
Students, yeah.
And these guys that hang around are regulars.
One of them, good player, and very German-looking with a very German name, Lowell Welch.
And he took a liking to me, and I took a liking to him.
And then Ed Christian, who was obviously Swedish, was also a good player and liked to play with me.
I gave him a good match.
He was an executive for the telephone company.
And also a skier.
He knew me from skiing, so I had an in.
Because the same people that play tennis in the Berkeley courts also were skiers.
The more affluent people, very athletic.
And that person knew me, had seen me at Sugar Bowl.
So he was a bachelor.
And we almost became friends to some degree.
You know, I just kind of kept my distance because I either didn't have any money or whatever.
But he did invite me to his place up at Tahoe a few times, opening and closing his chalet, driving his convertible to Tahoe.
And these students now, then the old Welsh, who took me to meet his family, his wife.
And he was a strange one.
He had these paraplegic children.
Oh, yes, right.
But he was always looking for girls for some reason.
But he was very shy and a very complex person, really.
He was not really a threat to anybody, but he would always chase some...
He was a looker.
I don't know what you call it.
He wouldn't really do anything about it because he had a little speech problem.
He stammered.
So he got right up to it, and then he couldn't speak.
Oh, yeah, he would hang around the Rose dancing.
He would go dancing.
He was a marvelous dancer.
And although he was married with three children, he would go dancing to the Rose.
Did you ever go dancing to him?
Yeah, he took me to the Rose.
I've got to tell you this.
Maybe I didn't.
I know I did.
I told you about the time when I was working in Berkeley, and I went to apply for a job.
I needed extra money.
I had a job, and I needed extra money.
And one of the gals that worked with me was when I was on Mandan.
I worked for this small company down in Portland, Alabama.
We went to the Rose Room ballroom to apply to be a dance hostess.
And the only reason I didn't get the job was because I couldn't afford the evening dance that you had to buy.
So I never really got it.
Because you saw a couple of shady characters standing nearby.
Very fair.
They sell their tickets.
Ten cents a dance.
So then this Turk would come around.
His name was Sadat Sermon.
Sadat Sermon.
Sadat Sermon.
We called him Sid.
And a real charmer with the boys.
He'd come, always new balls.
He was the only one that had new balls every time.
And tell these tales about his girlfriends.
We would always beat him badly, six-love, six-one.
And he says, oh, I'm too tired.
I had this last night.
Yeah, right.
And he's fat and orgy or whatever he is.
And Lowell and I would look at each other and say, this, we want to find out.
Sure.
How does he do that?
He was telling us he just had a divorce, but he spent the night with his ex-girl.
But he had this other girl over there and another one over there.
And he met some nurses.
And he, I mean, he was just, you know, our eyes were just like this.
So.
And he says, okay, let's go to Laval's and have some beer and pizza.
And it started to rain, and okay, let's go down there, fine.
And we'd order something, and we'd count our money a little bit, you know, we can't, never mind, never mind, just bring that over here, here, you know, pick up the check.
Hey, I mean, he was just...
We thought he had an oil well or something.
He was a rich student from Iran.
I guess it was back then.
It doesn't exist anymore.
Changed oil.
Changed oil.
And we knew his father was a minister of some kind.
One day, Lowell told me, you know, I found out where Sadat lives.
He would never tell us where he lives.
I always moved around.
I stayed there with my ex-wife.
These are really your kind of people, then.
Yeah.
They're moving from one place to the other.
